metadata.name: Winesburg, Ohio #103
metadata.description: “Winesburg, Ohio” is an act of uncanny place-making. The collection borrows its name from a 1919 short-story cycle by Sherwood Anderson, which explores a peculiar cast of characters living within a fictionalized, midwestern town. Like Anderson’s text, the “Winesburg, Ohio” algorithm constructs a world through recurring portrayals of specific structures and landmarks. Its scenes are populated by a variety of familiar elements taken from my larger body of work, including water towers, houses, and churches. Meanwhile, a series of scripted gestures insert abstract compositional elements into the outputs, counteracting their pictorial legibility. The strange landscapes that result are composite ideograms, comprised of multiple spatial possibilities that co-exist in varying states of contradiction.

metadata.name: Isometric Dreams #27
metadata.description:
"Isometric Dreams" is a visionary journey into the architectural essence of the mind's deepest narratives, set for release on the winter solstice, December 21st. This project invites viewers into a labyrinth of geometric splendor, mirroring the transition from the shortest day to the longest night.

The project comprises a series of digital canvases where light and shadow play across isometric landscapes, creating a cityscape of the subconscious. The vivid hues—fiery oranges, lush greens, and icy blues—burn and glow against the stark contrasts of shadow, symbolizing the ancient duality of the solstice: darkness surrendering to light.

On this most enigmatic of nights, when shadows stretch their longest and the veil between worlds grows thin, "Isometric Dreams" offers a visual homage to the mysteries of the unseen. The stark geometry, a nod to the order within chaos, contrasts with the swirling, dream-like quality of the overlaid patterns, suggests the intricate complexities of human cognition and the ethereal nature of our dreams.

Although the artworks in this project are static, they evoke dynamic emotional and subconscious experiences. Each piece, unchanging in form, sparks a personal journey of perception and interpretation, connecting the viewer's inner world with the timeless themes of light, time, and cognition.

3500x4953px
Press [s] for .jpeg | Press [p] for .png
Made with p5.js

Rob Scalera | 2023

metadata.name: Minima #220
metadata.description:
Minima is a study on focus and color. Playing with the idea of a simple composition of semicircles, either rotated up or down. The focus of the observer is moved with the use of gradual animation in the gradients and occasional circles and/or rectangles connecting the shapes together through color.

The name minima stems from the origins of the composition, mostly taking inspiration from minimalism in its use of a few elements to form a composition greater than the sum of its parts. Less is more, as they say.

The point at the bottom right of the canvas resembles the end of a sentence. Like reading a book, you process the canvas in a similar way, moving from what pops the most to what the least.

As the reader of this canvas I hope you observe what happens to your focus as the colors gradually move across the screen. The animations themselves are looping based on a noised sine wave, which gives them imperfections, imperfections you can observe.

----

Click / Tap on the bar at the bottom of the canvas to open up the GUI, used to export your minima into any format you want. Either .png or .svg. Ready for printing, if you desire.

ps. there might be a secret keyboard shortcut...

----

Minima,
Wouter Missler, 2022,
p5js + webgl.

metadata.name: Aftershock #121
metadata.description:
Turkey was hit by two devastating earthquakes at 6/02/2023 effecting multiple cities.

Aftershock is created to help and support people in earthquake region. 100% of the revenue from primary sales will be send to non governmental organization AHBAP after it's converted to ethereum. All donation will sent from atimtay.eth and will be shared publicly from my twitter account


Artwork info:

Aftershock is based on "Metropolix IX' algorithm. In Metropolis the parameter space was constrained and the cells were painted in a fashion which would create city silhouettes. In Aftershock i removed the constraints and changed the all rulesets and palettes which would give us chaos maybe you can call it a collapsed city.


Features:

6 color palettes and 1 monochrome 
3 subdivison levels 2,3,4 
2 aspect ratios 
10 divison styles 
and some other hidden randomized parameters which doesn't appear on the features but effecting overall outcome

Press 1 to 8 to export PNG at increasing resolution

Murat Atimtay 2023 www.atimtay.xyz

metadata.name: Qoqnus #71
metadata.description:
Qoqnus

In ancient Greek: φοῖνιξ
In Arabic: Al-Anqa
In English: Phoenix

The sacred bird is a legend that is mentioned in Iranian mythology, Greek mythology, Egyptian mythology, and Chinese mythology.
It is said that he is a rare and lonely bird and does not mate or reproduce. But once every thousand years, it spreads its wings on a large pile of firewood and sings, and when it is excited by its song, it lights a fire with its beak, and by burning in the fire from its ashes, another phoenix is ​​born.
In many cultures, the phoenix is ​​considered a symbol of immortality, sacrifice and long life.

In this work, I tried to create bird-like shapes that are being formed and created by using a grid in the form of noise and with the shape of rectangles that have random length and width and get their color from the palettes. You can clearly see the wings or the bird's head in most of the exits
In fact, my idea is to depict the moment of resurrection and rebirth of the phoenix from the heart of the ashes, which rises to the sky.
the ash particles around this reborn bird are being scattered in the air and finally from At the heart of this re-creation, a beautiful and glorious phoenix comes into existence.

Made by p5.js
